Comment:
Of note you can immediately see that the technology does not function properly, and it's getting a stigma which creates more problems than it solves.

Many times during the video it showed students with a recognizable amount of focus on the teacher and activities... but it showed up blue as though they were distracted. Other times it showed students clearly distracted by the cameras in the classroom, but it never phased from yellow as though they were focused. Which leads to the final point on this, being "focused" is an abstract, and it's relative. A gamer that is playing games instead of doing their homework is likely to be VERY focused, but they're not focused on the correct thing. The headbands, with only 3 points of data, is not going to do well at distinguishing the correct focus. 

But the stigma is the other problem, these headbands can help teachers and researchers understand things and the needs of an individual child, allowing them to curate and perfect teaching methods and helping find and assist kids who are silently struggling with the material, however the approach of monitoring the activity and sending it to the parents of everybody in the class ranking kids against each other is ten steps back. All it does is, sadly, distract kids from properly learning in the class as their parents are needlessly harsh on them in class.

Teaching IS a relative issue, I was so far ahead of the peers in my classes that I typically had the highest grades and paid the least amount of attention. This system may have looked at me and said "well he ranks really low" and shamed me in front of the other kids and their parents in class. But would I just be the anomaly, or would the system properly assist me in getting even better grades?

The reality is here is that the classroom is a woefully inefficient way to teach people, certain kids do well in large instruction environments where a teacher tells you facts and writes some things on the board and hands out a sheet of paper and every time you have a question you're limited in the amount of responses you can get forcing you to work harder. Other people want an environment where they have the tools to ask themselves the questions, ask a source of knowledge the questions and not have to worry about others being a factor teacher or otherwise. I didn't pay attention in class because I only paid attention to new information, until you put a problem in front of me to solve with the information, I didn't care about it. So it wasn't until you gave me the homework or the classwork that I could physically contribute attention. It didn't make me a bad student in the long run, but it frustrated teachers that spent a long lecture looking at me sleeping just to wake up and open the book and go over the information they already spent time explaining once they paperwork hit.

These students are going to be stigmatized into oblivion, you'll get positive results from some, but you'll get mental disorder from others, and yet others will have their grades worsen as they become more focused on the headset's scoring than the actual information being taught. Sprinkle on the lack of accuracy the headsets provide and you've got yourself a room full of human guinea pigs that will be tossed aside by society at the end of it.

Comment: At the end of the day, it boils down to whether you care more about results or ethics. It seems difficult to doubt the Chinese way shown in this story does indeed get better results - particularly short-term immediately measurable-by-objective-numbers results.  How much freedom should we sacrifice in order to get superior results? And if it's unethical to punish kids for doing worse in the short-term simply for not paying attention in class, then how can we say results are more important than anything else in workplace performance, social competence, etc? Also, I'd say its no worse than society dishing out social penalties to the odd, strange, non-conformist, etc. At least the Chinese way serves a practical purpose, whereas forcing those who won't or can't conform to social ideas of "normal behavior (in the judgmental sense)" is based on nitpicky, non-character aspects of who a person is.

All this setup is just clowning the people with the EEG tech and also the use of AI as well, since the training data collected from here would not even be usable from its low accuracy and precision on representing real data. Comment:
Reports & documentaries like this make me cringe in fright. Perhaps, we might be building smarter students, but at what cost? How prepared are we for the possible consequences in the long-term?

There a number of immediate red flags that are obvious in the development and applications of #ArtificialIntelligence way... From a #TechnologyGovernance and #DigitalDevelopment perspective, so many unanswered questions are particularly troubling:

1) How are the #Data generated by these #Devices used...?
2) How are they stored and transmitted...?
3) What happens to the data after the learning relationship between the school and the student has ended...?
4) Who holds #Control or #Sovreignty over these data...? The students? Their parents? The #government? The #TechCompanies that produce the devices?
5) What standards & regulations are applied in the development & applications of these devices...?

No one would want to see their child disqualified or denied a job placement many decades later, simply because an AI system revealed to potential employers that the person seemed to have had issues with attention span & concentration as a college student many years ago.

I have advocated for an approach to #AlgorithmicIntegrity in #MachineLearning applications of Big Data for #ArtificialIntelligence, as a way of building greater trust in the behavior of #AI without obscuring the utilities of #ML and #BD for problem-solving...

A recent Article that I wrote describing this Approach in practical detail was selected runner-up in the 2020 Future Leaders Competition of the @The_IIC...

Comment:
This system is called Neurofeedback in Switzerland. It's a treatment for people with ADHD. You watch a video clip while having electrodes on your head. When you loose focus, the clip stops and you have to focus again to continue the clip. It's a very great alternative to medication like Ritalin, because one should not depend on Ritalin for a lifetime. 

Meanwhile the US prescribes amphetamine and crystal meth for ADHD next to methylphenidate (Ritalin).

And US media talking about DATA PRIVACY? The data goes to the Chinese government who funds this research and development. It's not going to be traded and sold like US companies casually do. Who are they going to sell their information to? E.g. China forces Apple to keep Chinese iPhone user data in China and nowhere else , because the state actually cares about data privacy and that it should not be in the wrong hands.

Comment: i bought this in reseda record trader, reseda blvd, reseda, san fernando valley, (the valley),  L.A. in may 1994 for $5.99 promotion only, not for sale stamped on it. spent hours on end in there digging in the bargain bin the yanks werent interested in. still got it. found some gems, rare stuff, all promo only, not for sale embossed on them at giveaway price. $1.99 up to $7.99 when cds sold at $20 new. all the mugs were down at tower records on sunset blvd. shout out to record trader in RESEDA baby. punk was big in L.A. early 90s. try explaining 'electronic trip music' to that lot. the looks i got. came back to london in 1996 with suitcases full. had to pay excess baggage on the plane. couldnt part with them. still got 'em. warp rereleased artificial intelligence 30 year anniversay today so i looked this one up on youtube. im 53 and still into it.
